-in the law and in the rest of life. Drawing on examples from an unusual range of sources--judicial opinions, children's essays, literature, politics, and the speech-out-of-silence of Quaker worship--White offers a fascinating analysis of the force of our languages. Reminding us that every moment of speech is an occasion for gaining control of what we say and who we are, he shows us that we must practice the art of resisting the forces of inhumanity built into our habits of speech and thought if we are to become more capable of love and justice--in both law and life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJudgmentszUnited States. 0aLawxLanguage. 0aViolence in literature. 0aViolence. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082753440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400827534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400827534.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK